There’s an interesting distinction in what you’re pointing at.

Many people are constrained less by actual external limits than by anticipated limits—imagining embarrassment, rejection, failure, or judgment before they act. If those imagined consequences dominate your decisions, they can shrink your freedom more than reality itself.

A useful way to think about it is:

* Question assumptions before treating them as constraints.
* Distinguish real consequences (laws, safety, ethics, commitments, physical limits) from imagined consequences (what if they laugh, what if I fail, what if I’m not ready).
* Take actions that are reversible when possible, so you learn from reality instead of your predictions.
* Let evidence update your model rather than letting fear freeze it.

That doesn’t mean acting without regard for consequences. Radical freedom isn’t the absence of constraints—it’s choosing deliberately which constraints are worth respecting. Some are imposed by physics, some by society, some by your own values, and some are simply stories your mind tells.

So a formulation I like is:

“Have the courage to test your assumptions. Respect real consequences, not imaginary ones.”

Or, even shorter:

“Don’t let hypothetical fear outrank reality.”

That preserves boldness without confusing recklessness for freedom.